        "assistant": "# Prismatic Affinity\n\nThe term \"prismatic affinity\" appears in a few different contexts, so the meaning depends on what field you're asking about:\n\n## In Mathematics / Algebraic Geometry\n**Prismatic cohomology** is a theory developed by Bhargav Bhatt and Peter Scholze that unifies various p-adic cohomology theories. While \"prismatic affinity\" isn't a standard term here, related concepts involve **prisms** (pairs (A, I) where A is a δ-ring and I is an invertible ideal satisfying certain conditions) and morphisms between them.\n\n## In Crystallography / Materials Science\nIt can informally refer to the tendency of certain minerals or crystals to form **prismatic shapes** (elongated, with parallel faces) due to their internal atomic structure and bonding preferences.\n\n## In Gaming / Fantasy Contexts\nIn games like *Magic: The Gathering*, *World of Warcraft*, or various RPGs, \"prismatic\" refers to multi-colored or all-element effects, and an \"affinity\" is a mechanic that grants bonuses based on what you control. A \"prismatic affinity\" would be a bonus tied to having multiple colors/elements.\n\n## In Optics\nLoosely, it could describe how light has an \"affinity\" to split into its component wavelengths when passing through a prism (dispersion).\n\n---\n\nCould you tell me **what context** you encountered this term in? I can give you a much more precise answer if I know whether you're asking about math, gaming, mineralogy, or something else.",
