        "assistant": "Using the definition you've stipulated, the difference comes down to **determinacy** and **structure**:\n\n## Ambiguity\n- The meaning or identity of the object is **undecided** — there are multiple candidate readings, and nothing in the act of attention settles which one applies.\n- The observer is left in a state of interpretive suspension (or makes an arbitrary choice).\n- Classic example: the duck-rabbit figure considered as \"ambiguous\" — is it a duck or a rabbit? The image itself doesn't commit.\n- Ambiguity is a property of *underdetermination*: insufficient constraint to fix a reading.\n\n## Prismatic Affinity\n- The object's apparent identity is **fully determinate under each framing** — there's nothing undecided within a given angle of attention.\n- The shift across framings is **coherent**, not arbitrary: changing the angle of attention reliably produces a different but internally consistent description.\n- Two observers attending under different framings don't disagree about an unsettled meaning; each is producing a complete, well-formed account of the object as it appears under their framing.\n- The descriptions are **non-overlapping** yet neither is wrong — they're answers to differently-framed questions about the same object.\n\n## The Core Contrast\n\n| | Ambiguity | Prismatic Affinity |\n|---|---|---|\n| Meaning under a given reading | Unsettled | Fully determinate |\n| Source of multiplicity | Lack of constraint | Structured response to framing |\n| Relation between readings | Competing candidates | Coherent variants |\n| Resolution | Requires disambiguation | Requires no resolution; each framing is complete |\n\nPut compactly: **ambiguity is a deficit of determination; prismatic affinity is a surplus of coherent determinations**, each indexed to a way of attending.\n\nA useful test: if asking \"but which one is it *really*?\" feels like a legitimate demand, you're likely dealing with ambiguity. If that question feels like a 