        "user": "How does \"prismatic affinity\" differ from perspectivism / perspective-dependence?",
        "assistant": "Using your stipulated definition, the difference turns on **what varies** and **what generates the variation**:\n\n## Perspective-Dependence\n- Variation is driven by the observer's **position, location, or standpoint** — spatial, temporal, social, epistemic, or cultural.\n- The object remains in some sense \"the same\" across perspectives; what changes is the *vantage* from which it's apprehended.\n- Different perspectives typically yield **partial views** that can, in principle, be aggregated, triangulated, or reconciled into a fuller account.\n- Classic examples: seeing a building from the north vs. the south; a historical event described by victor vs. vanquished; Nagel's \"view from nowhere\" as the limit-concept against which perspectives are measured.\n- The structure is fundamentally **indexical**: descriptions are tied to *where the observer is*.\n\n## Prismatic Affinity\n- Variation is driven by the **angle of attention or framing** — *how* the object is being attended to, not *where from*.\n- The object's **apparent identity itself shifts**, not just its appearance from a vantage. Different framings don't reveal different sides of one fixed thing; they constitute different coherent identities.\n- Descriptions across framings are **non-overlapping** rather than partial — they aren't pieces that sum to a whole.\n- Two observers in the *same position* can produce divergent prismatic descriptions if their framings differ; conversely, two observers in different positions can produce the same description if their framings align.\n- The structure is **attentional/constitutive**, not indexical.\n\n## The Core Contrast\n\n| | Perspective-Dependence | Prismatic Affinity |\n|---|---|---|\n| What varies | Observer's position/standpoint | Angle of attention / framing |\n| Status of the object | Stable; appearances vary | Apparent identity itself shifts |\n| Relation between accounts | Partial, aggregable, triangulable | Non-overlapping, internally complete |\n| Implied limit-concept | A fuller or \"total\" view | No totalization; each framing is whole |\n| Move that resolves disagreement | Change position or combine views | None needed — framings aren't in competition |\n\n## A Diagnostic\n\n- **Perspective-dependence** invites the question: *\"What would it look like from elsewhere — or from everywhere?\"* The implicit ideal is synthesis.\n- **Prismatic affinity** makes that question malformed. There is no \"elsewhere\" to move to, because the variation isn't spatial or positional; and there is no synthesis to aim at, because the descriptions aren't partial views of a common substrate — they're complete identities indexed to framings.\n\nPut compactly: **perspective-dependence multiplies views of one object; prismatic affinity multiplies coherent identities under one object's exposure to differently angled attention.**\n\nA subtler way to mark the line: perspective-dependence is compatible with realism about a single underlying object whose properties are merely *accessed* differently. Prismatic affinity, by contrast, suggests the object's identity is *constituted* in concert with the framing — closer in spirit to Goodman's worldmaking or aspect-perception than to standpoint epistemology, though still distinct from each.",
