        "assistant": "Using your stipulated definition, the difference turns on **what bears the multiplicity** and **how the multiplicity is structured**:\n\n## Polysemy\n- A property of **linguistic signs** — a single word or expression carries multiple related senses (e.g., \"mouth\" of a person vs. \"mouth\" of a river; \"bank\" as financial institution vs. riverbank in the historically related sense).\n- The multiple senses are **lexically encoded** — stored, conventional, listable. A competent speaker knows them as a finite (if fuzzy) inventory.\n- Context typically **selects** one sense; the others recede. The senses don't co-activate as a coherent whole.\n- The relations among senses are often metaphorical, metonymic, or genealogical — traceable through semantic extension.\n- The locus of multiplicity is the **sign**, not the object or the act of attention.\n\n## Prismatic Affinity\n- A property of the **perceived object** under attention — not of a word used to denote it.\n- The multiple identities are **not pre-stored or conventional** — they are generated by the angle of attention itself, and need not form a finite or listable inventory.\n- Different framings don't compete for selection the way polysemous senses do; each framing yields a complete identity that doesn't need to be \"chosen over\" the others.\n- The relations among framings are **structural/attentional**, not semantic-genealogical. They aren't extensions of a base meaning.\n- The locus of multiplicity is the **object-as-attended**, not the linguistic vehicle.\n\n## The Core Contrast\n\n| | Polysemy | Prismatic Affinity |\n|---|---|---|\n| What carries the multiplicity | A linguistic sign | A perceived object under attention |\n| Source of the multiplicity | Lexical convention / semantic extension | Angle of attention / framing |\n| Inventory | Finite, listable, learned | Open-ended, generated, not stored |\n| Resolution mechanism | Context selects one sense | No selection needed; framings don't compete |\n| Relation among variants | Metaphorical/metonymic kinship | Structural variants of attentional uptake |\n| Domain | Semantics / lexicography | Phenomenology / philosophy of perception |\n\n## A Diagnostic\n\n- For **polysemy**, you can usually answer: *\"How many senses does this word have, and how are they related?\"* — and the answer is in principle dictionary-like.\n- For **prismatic affinity**, that question misfires. There's no enumeration of \"the framings\" the object admits; framings aren't lexical entries but ways of attending, and the object's identities under them are generated, not retrieved.\n\n## A Subtler Point\n\nPolysemy can be a *symptom* but is not the thing itself. If an object exhibits prismatic affinity, the words we use to describe it under different framings may end up looking polysemous — but the polysemy would be a downstream linguistic shadow of an upstream attentional phenomenon. Polysemy lives in the lexicon; prismatic affinity lives in the encounter.\n\nPut compactly: **polysemy is one sign harboring many conventional senses; prismatic affinity is one object yielding many coherent identities under differently angled attention.** The first is a fact about language; the second is a fact about how attention constitutes what it attends to.\n\nOne caveat worth flagging: I'm reasoning entirely from the definition you stipulated. The contrasts above are internally consistent with that definition, but I'd resist claiming they reflect an established consensus, since I have no independent source for \"prismatic affinity\" as a technical term.",
