        "assistant": "# Prismatic Affinity\n\nA **prismatic affinity** is a concept from geometry, specifically within the field of affine transformations. It refers to a particular type of affine transformation that has special structural properties analogous to a geometric prism.\n\n## Definition\n\nIn its most common formulation, a prismatic affinity (also called a *shear affinity* or *axial affinity*) is an affine transformation of space (typically 3D) that:\n\n- **Fixes a plane** pointwise (called the **axis plane** or **base plane**)\n- **Maps every line in a fixed direction** (the *direction of the affinity*) to itself\n- The direction is generally **not perpendicular** to the axis plane (otherwise it would be a special case like an orthogonal affinity)\n\nIn 2D, the analogous concept involves an affine transformation that fixes a line pointwise and shifts points along a fixed direction, with displacement proportional to the distance from the fixed line.\n\n## Key Properties\n\n1. **Parallelism is preserved** (as with all affine transformations)\n2. **Ratios along parallel lines** are preserved\n3. **The ratio of affinity** (a scalar *k*) determines how far points move: a point at distance *d* from the fixed plane moves to a position whose projection onto the direction is scaled by *k*\n4. When *k* = 1, the transformation is the identity; when *k* = -1, it becomes a kind of reflection\n\n## Example\n\nA simple 2D example: the transformation\n$$(x, y) \\mapsto (x + ky, y)$$\n\nfixes the x-axis (where *y* = 0) and shears points horizontally in proportion to their *y*-coordinate. This is a prismatic (or shear) affinity with the x-axis as its axis and the x-direction as its direction.\n\n## Context\n\nPrismatic affinities appear in:\n- **Descriptive geometry** and technical drawing\n- **Projective and affine geometry** courses\n- **Computer graphics** (as shear transformations)\n- **Crystallography** when describing certain symmetry operations\n\nWere you asking 